description: Stitch: @si  Bi-weekly payments can actually reduce the amount of interest you owe on the life of a loan as well as the total term you need to pay it. That’s because with bi-weekly payments you are making one extra monthly payment throughout the course of a year - which lessens you overall loan burden, and thus, interest. From Mortgage Retirement Professor: “For example, the monthly payment on a $100,000 8% loan for 30 years is $733.77. On a biweekly payment plan, you’d pay half this amount every two weeks, or 26 payments over a year. This is the equivalent of one extra monthly payment — 13 instead of 12. You’d pay off your loan in 277 months, rather than 360 and save $44,160 in interest payments.”

description: This is the worst type of credit card: retail store credit cards… but there are some good ones ⬇️ First off, a lot of retail store cards will try to get you to sign up for a short term reward - such as a 20% off, or $20 dollars off whenever you sign up. One trap is that often times there are exclusion lists on the items that qualify for those rewards.  Retail store card rewards are short-lived because the interest rates on store credit cards can often be double the APR of a generalized credit card. And if you ask me, I’d rather get points for a purchase so that I can take a free vacation instead of getting say, $100 off at a store. If you are going to get a retail store credit card, make sure it makes sense for you, and run the numbers on if your spend will actually get you *that* much in cash back. Some of the better retail store cards in my opinion are: 1. The Costco Card 2. The Amazon Card 3. The Target Card
